<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-352-666  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 352 666.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  June 7 1989 n1464 p12(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>What price to pay for microwave frequency?andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wilson, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The British government invites the microwave industry toparticipate in a discussion on the choice of a frequency band forlow-power microwave television transmission.andP;  The 2.5G-Hz and27-29G-Hz bands have already been ruled out because they arecurrently in use.andP;  Higher frequencies are underused and moreattractive to the government, but require sophisticated, unprovenequipment to operate.andP;  The 40G-Hz frequencies can only cover a 2.5mile radius from a single transmitter, while the 12G-Hz frequencyhas a range of up to 20 miles.andP;  40G-Hz systems can only be used ifthey are integrated with fiber-optic cable networks for linkinglocal transmitters.andP;  The frequency debate raging in the UK hasbeen partially solved in Canada with the announcement of 2.5 GHzcommercial microwave video distribution system from GEC PlesseyTelecommunications' Canadian subsidiary.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Microwave CommunicationsTelevisionVideo SystemsBroadcastingFrequencyStandards.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   The North American blueprint for low-power multipoint microwave(chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>